  <h2 id="verdict">Our Verdict</h2>
  <p>
    Both AXA Global and BUPA Global are excellent insurance providers. This comparison is between two premium options, not good versus bad. Either will provide comprehensive international health coverage from financially stable, reputable insurers.
  </p>
  <p>
    <strong>AXA Global</strong> offers the better value proposition for most expats. You get comprehensive coverage, EU regulatory benefits, and solid service at 30-40% lower premiums than BUPA. For healthy people without specific needs that BUPA serves better, AXA is the smart choice. The savings compound over years of coverage.
  </p>
  <p>
    <strong>BUPA Global</strong> justifies its premium pricing for specific needs. If mental health coverage is important to you—whether for existing needs or as a priority given expat stresses—BUPA's industry-leading benefits may be worth the premium. If you have pre-existing conditions you want covered, BUPA's full underwriting offers possibilities AXA's moratorium approach cannot. If exceptional service matters and you can afford it, BUPA delivers.
  </p>
  <p>
    Our recommendation for most expats: <strong>AXA Global</strong> offers better value. Save the 30-40% unless you specifically need what BUPA offers.
  </p>
  <p>
    The exceptions: Choose <strong>BUPA</strong> if mental health is an active priority, if you have pre-existing conditions requiring coverage, or if premium service genuinely matters to you and money is secondary.
  </p>

